/ Future Instruments 2214

.container

  .instruments.blur.js-instruments

    - instruments_array = data.instruments.to_a
  
    - instruments_array.shuffle.each_with_index do |instrument, index|

      - instrument = instrument[1]

      .slide.js-slide{:class => [("active" if index == 0), instrument.shade]}

        .slide--bg--blurred.js-slide-bg-blurred{:style => 'background-image: url(' + instrument.image_blurred + ')'}

        .slide--bg.js-slide-bg{:style => 'background-image: url(' + instrument.image + ')'}

        %h2.author= instrument.author

        .instrument--overlay--bg.js-instrument-overlay-bg

        .instrument--overlay.js-instrument-overlay

          .instrument--info

            %h2= instrument.title

            = instrument.info

            %p
              By #{instrument.author}

            .share--buttons
              %a.share--facebook{:href => '#'}
              %a.share--twitter{:href => '#'}
              %a.share--google{:href => '#'}
              %a.share--email{:href => '#'}

        .instrument--overlay--top-gradient.js-overlay-top-gradient

    .control.pagination.prev.js-prev

    .control.pagination.next.js-next

    .control.info.js-info

    %nav.nav--overlay.js-nav
      %h2.nav--title

        %button.nav--item.js-about
          About — Future Instruments 2214

    .about--overlay.js-about-overlay

      .about--content

        %p A Red Bull Music Academy project, for Tokyo 2014

        %p
          So in this case, we would have instant access to all music everywhere. Everything would be collaborative. People won’t just consume music, but participate. As everything is hyperconnected, nothing is passive. Everything would contain feedback loops. We’ll be less likely to share whole songs, written by one person, but hooks and melodies and beats would go viral and be interpreted en masse, and the piece of music would be an emergent property of these patterns.

        %p Images all by Kim Laughton

